  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries adopt similar legal approaches and definitions\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Mutual legal assistance mechanisms\n- Consistent anti-money laundering (AML) compliance protocols\n\n3. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Joint investigations\n- Extradition agreements\n- Coordinated asset seizure and recovery efforts\n\n4. Legal Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International transaction monitoring\n\n5. Transnational Legal Mechanisms\n- International Criminal Court\n- Interpol coordination\n- Global financial intelligence units\n- Diplomatic channels for legal cooperation\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering across different jurisdictions.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects?",
